===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A [[shout]] of [[approbation]], favor, or assent; eager expression of [[approval]]; loud [[applause]].
#* '''1876''', {{w|Henry Martyn Robert}}, ''{{w|Robert’s Rules of Order}}'', Chicago: S.C. Griggs & Co., p. 100, Article IX, Section 46, note,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/9097/pg9097-images.html]</sup>
#*: Sometimes a member nominates a chairman and no vote is taken, the assembly signifying their approval by '''acclamation'''.
#* {{RQ:Southey Thomas More|volume=I|page=118|passage=On such a day, a holyday having been voted by '''acclamation''', an ordinary walk would not satisfy the children:..it must be a scramble among the mountains, and I must accompany them; {{...}}}}
# The act of winning an election to a post because there were no other [[candidate]]s.
#: ''With no one running against her, she won by '''acclamation'''''.
# {{lb|en|art}} A representation, in [[sculpture]] or on [[medals]], of people expressing joy.
#* '''1826''', {{w|James Elmes}}, ''A General and Bibliographical Dictionary of the Fine Arts''
#*: The medals on which laudatory '''acclamations''' are recorded are called by antiquaries '''acclamation''' medals.
# {{lb|en|political}} An [[oral]] [[vote]] taken without formal [[ballot]] and with much fanfare; typically an overwhelmingly affirmative vote.

